Actually... here in the US 12 people are asked to decide if someone is &quot;guilty beyond a reasonable doubt&quot; ...not might have... not probably did... not I am almost certain... but beyond a reasonable doubt. And if 1... just 1... for whatever reason isn't 100 percent sure... then they are not found guilty. Then if the death penalty is sentenced, they are given an automatic appeal, so that means 12 more people will be given the chance to hear the case, the evidence, and again must decide that soandso did this horrible act &quot;beyond a reasonable doubt&quot; So that means 24 people are 100 percent certain that soandso is guilty. On top of that there are tons of checks and balances (appeals to sup. court, governors, etc)that are placed there to do our very best to be certain that no one slips thru the system that is innocent. Is it perfect? No, but its DAMNED rare that innocent people are sentenced to death and actually put to death.<br>
<br>
Also keep in mind, our CJ system isn't based on &quot;reforming&quot; the criminal. That was tried at the turn of the century and was a dismal failure. Should we be trying to reform criminals? That is for smarter people than me to answer, but the fact is our system isn't based on that. Our system is based on deterrents, and that for certain acts, punishment will be given out to the criminal equal to the crime. So saying that locking someone up for 10 years doesn't teach them anything... well that doesn't hold water because that isn't why we lock people up... or put them to death for that matter.<br>
<br>
My personal opinion is that in some cases the death penalty is the right punishment, and fits the crime. Some people have committed such horrible acts that they have given up the right to live on this rock. (i.e. the fellow that killed those little girls and raped his sons girlfriend) So I guess I am for it, but this should be our highest and most rarely used form on justice... and should be reserve for only the most horrible criminals in the country. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/upanamah.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Panamah</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sneaky Pants</span><br>  Posts: 246<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/30/02 2:03:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3634.topic&index=22>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://nmcs.com/kingscourt/images/panamah_head.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: A Fundamental Right Many Are Being Denied</span><hr size=1> You only have to look as far as the OJ trial to see an example of how the rich can buy their freedom.  It's the poor people with bad representation that don't have a chance.  They're the ones we execute.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
